To master professionalism and academic communication, you should focus on books that bridge the gap between student life and the expectations of professors or future employers. These resources provide the "hidden rules" of etiquette, especially for technical students.
Essential Professionalism for Students
These books are designed specifically to help students transition into professional environments by explaining behavioral expectations.

100 Things You Need to Know: Professionalism: For Students and New Professionals by Mary Crane
This book breaks down critical skills that many graduates lack, such as how to think through problems or behave in front of clients and superiors.
It is organized into short, easy-to-absorb chunks, making it a quick but highly practical read for busy students.

The Professional by Subroto Bagchi
A classic recommended for understanding the mindset of a professional. It focuses on integrity, self-regulation, and the "true" meaning of professional conduct beyond just technical skill.
Professionalism, Professional Values and Ethics Including Bioethics
According to amazon.in, this book focuses on the ethical foundations and core values of a professional, which is essential for students facing academic council standards. 
